<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ANGELES TEACHERS' STRIKE SETTLEMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This strike has been an education in the truest sense of the word. However, 
this one had little to do with books and pencils. 
</P>
<P>
As educators we have precious little time to spend with one another but we 
won't soon forget one memorable exception. Those of us on strike from my school 
went to breakfast one morning after picketing to assess how we were holding up 
as a group. At that time we each shared our feelings about continuing our 
resolve to stay on strike and the discussion started to grow into something 
else. 
</P>
<P>
Our sharings made me truly proud to be in this beleaguered profession. We spoke 
about ours being one of the most important jobs on the planet. We spoke of 
being separated from those little faces that came to the fence every day and we 
were grieving. There was a growing awareness of real professional pride among 
us. 
</P>
<P>
Something happened that morning and the strike had actually brought us a gift. 
We can now go back to our school knowing we bring with us pride, a sense of 
trust and dignity. At the ratification rally I felt all teachers in Los Angeles 
had gained this and no one can take that away from us now. 
</P>
<P>
PAT TOBIAS 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
