<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. URGED TO REDUCE FORCES IN S. KOREA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A member of the Senate Armed Services Committee on Friday suggested reducing 
U.S. forces stationed in South Korea and requiring Tokyo to foot the full bill 
for keeping American troops in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
"The United States can no longer sustain a disproportionate burden of 
maintaining a common defense for the free world," said Sen. Carl Levin 
(D-Mich). He is chairman of the Armed Services subcommittee on conventional 
forces and alliance defense. 
</P>
<P>
Levin said in an interview with reporters that he will make his proposals in 
the form of a "sense of the Senate" resolution that reflects the Senate's 
sentiment but has no legal authority. 
</P>
<P>
Specifically, Levin is proposing that the Bush Administration discuss with 
South Korea a timetable "for a mutually acceptable . . . partial reduction of 
our forces" and a plan to replace the U.S. commander who has operational 
control over Korean forces with a South Korean general. 
</P>
<P>
Levin estimated that the 43,000 U.S. troops in South Korea could be reduced to 
about 10,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
