<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO INDUSTRY NOTES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Noble Broadcast Group of San Diego and the Griffin Group of Los Angeles have 
called off a purchase agreement announced in April whereby Griffin was to have 
bought two Boston radio stations, WSSH-FM and WKKU-AM, from Noble for $39 
million. 
</P>
<P>
Noble said in a statement that it backed out of the Griffin deal after its 
efforts to buy two radio networks in a separate transaction failed. Proceeds 
from the sale of the stations to the group controlled by entertainer Merv 
Griffin were to have been used to finance the purchase of the networks. 
</P>
<P>
Noble, which bought the stations for a combined price of $22.2 million in 1986 
and 1987, owns 18 radio stations. Griffin owns four radio stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
