<HEADLINE>
<P>
AGOURA TO FACE BIG BEAR FOR SOFTBALL TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE GLAZE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When Coach Linda Moule took over as Agoura High softball coach last year, she 
inherited a team that had won only one game in the two previous seasons. 
</P>
<P>
Moule, who coached the Chargers' junior varsity in 1987, has since turned the 
program around. 
</P>
<P>
Agoura tied Santa Paula for the Frontier League championship in 1988 and won 
the title outright this year with a 9-0 league record. The Chargers last won 
the league crown in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
Now Agoura (22-2), which had never survived the first round of the Southern 
Section playoffs, will play for the 1-A Division championship. The Chargers, 
winners of 19 in a row after starting the season 3-2, will play second-seeded 
Big Bear at 2:30 p.m. Saturday at Mayfair Park in Lakewood. 
</P>
<P>
Because they lack experience in a major tournament championship, the Chargers 
are slightly numb to the feeling. 
</P>
<P>
"I know they're excited," Moule said. "But I don't think the real meaning of it 
has hit them yet." 
</P>
<P>
The realization should have sunk in Tuesday when Agoura eliminated top-seeded 
Paraclete, 10-3, in a semifinal. Big Bear defeated St. Bonaventure, 5-1, in the 
other semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
Big Bear (22-3) is no stranger to postseason play. The defending Small Schools 
Division champion is making its fifth consecutive playoff appearance. 
</P>
<P>
Agoura (22-2), the fourth-seeded team, will rely on pitcher Melissa Thatcher -- 
the Frontier League's most valuable player -- in its attempt to dethrone Big 
Bear. 
</P>
<P>
Thatcher (22-2), who has an earned-run average of 0.56 and averages six 
strikeouts a game, threw a four-hitter and struck out four against Paraclete. 
The sophomore right-hander is a low-ball pitcher who gets a lot of outs on 
ground balls. 
</P>
<P>
Big Bear, the De Anza League champion, will counter with starter Marjie Sievers 
(20-3), who has struck out 199 of the 547 batters she has faced this season. 
</P>
<P>
The Chargers are led by catcher Lisa Little, the only senior on the team and, 
according to her coach, a sound defensive player. "We haven't had very many 
people steal against us this year," Moule said, adding that at 6-foot-1 she 
blocks the plate well. "If she puts her shoulder down, you can forget it." 
</P>
<P>
Little (.430 batting average) Jill Hartwig (.380) and Leslie North (.400) are 
the team's top batters. Wendy Baertschiger had three hits against Paraclete. 
</P>
<P>
Big Bear's Chelcee Clifton, Coach Mike Clifton's daughter, is batting a 
team-high .635 and has five home runs. She is also the team leader in runs 
batted in (39) and runs scored (40). 
</P>
</TEXT>
